    </note>
    <example id="exam-00009">
    <title>Finding Altitude</title>
    <exercise id="exer-00017">
    <problem id="prob-00017">
    <para id="para-00063">A small plane takes off from an airport at an angle of <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><mrow><msup><mrow><mn>31.3</mn></mrow><mo>∘</mo></msup></mrow></math> to the ground. About two-thirds of a mile (3520 ft) from the airport is an 1,100-ft peak in the flight path of the plane (Figure 10.XX). If the plane continues that angle of ascent, find its altitude when it is above the peak, and how far it will be above the peak.</para>
    <figure id="fig-00017" xmlns="http://cnx.rice.edu/cnxml">
    <media alt="Insert Alt Text">
    <image mime-type="image/png" src="../../media/CS_Figure_10_08_UN017.png"/>
    </media>
    <caption/>
    </figure>
    </problem>
    <solution id="sol-00009">
    <para id="para-00064">To solve this problem, we use the tangent function:
    <equation id="eq-00021"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><mtable columnspacing="0.3em"><mtr><mtd columnalign="right"><mi>tan</mi><msup><mn>31.3</mn><mo>∘</mo></msup></mtd><mtd columnalign="center"><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd columnalign="left"><mfrac><mi>x</mi><mrow><mn>3520</mn></mrow></mfrac></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd columnalign="right"><mn>3520</mn><mi>tan</mi><msup><mn>31.3</mn><mo>∘</mo></msup></mtd><mtd columnalign="center"><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd columnalign="left"><mn>2140</mn></mtd></mtr></mtable></math></equation></para>
    <para id="para-00065" xmlns="http://cnx.rice.edu/cnxml">The plane’s altitude when passing over the peak is 2,140 ft, and it is 1,040 ft above the peak.</para>
    </solution>
    </exercise>
    </example>
