    <example id="exam-00010">
    <title>Finding Unknown Sides and Angles</title>
    <exercise id="exer-00019">
    <problem id="prob-00019">
    <para id="para-00067">Suppose you have two known sides, but do not know the measure of any angles except for the right angle (Figure 10.XX). Find the measure of the unknown angles and the third side.</para>
    <figure id="fig-00018">
    <media alt="Insert Alt Text">
    <image mime-type="image/png" src="../../media/CS_Figure_10_08_UN018.png"/>
    </media>
    <caption/>
    </figure>
    </problem>
    <solution id="sol-00010">
    <para id="para-00068"><emphasis effect="bold">Step 1:</emphasis> We can find the third side using the Pythagorean Theorem:
    <equation id="eq-00022"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><mtable columnspacing="0.3em"><mtr><mtd columnalign="right"><msup><mn>6</mn><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mn>4</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></mtd><mtd columnalign="center"><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd columnalign="left"><msup><mi>c</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd columnalign="right"><mn>52</mn></mtd><mtd columnalign="center"><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd columnalign="left"><msup><mi>c</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd columnalign="right"><mn>2</mn><msqrt><mrow><mn>13</mn></mrow></msqrt></mtd><mtd columnalign="center"><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd columnalign="left"><mi>c</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable></math></equation></para>
    <para id="para-00069" xmlns="http://cnx.rice.edu/cnxml">Now, we have all three sides.</para>
    <para id="para-00070"><emphasis effect="bold">Step 2:</emphasis> To find <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><mrow><mi>θ</mi><mo>,</mo></mrow></math> we will first find <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><mrow><mi>sin</mi><mi>θ</mi><mo>.</mo></mrow></math>
    <equation id="eq-00023" xmlns="http://cnx.rice.edu/cnxml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><mrow><mtable columnspacing="0.3em"><mtr><mtd columnalign="right"><mi>sin</mi><mi>θ</mi></mtd><mtd columnalign="center"><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd columnalign="left"><mfrac><mrow><mi>o</mi><mi>p</mi><mi>p</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>h</mi><mi>y</mi><mi>p</mi></mrow></mfrac></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd columnalign="right"/><mtd columnalign="center"><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd columnalign="left"><mfrac><mn>4</mn><mrow><mn>2</mn><msqrt><mrow><mn>13</mn></mrow></msqrt></mrow></mfrac></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd columnalign="right"/><mtd columnalign="center"><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd columnalign="left"><mfrac><mn>2</mn><mrow><msqrt><mrow><mn>13</mn></mrow></msqrt></mrow></mfrac><mo>.</mo></mtd></mtr></mtable></mrow></math></equation></para>
    <para id="para-00071" xmlns="http://cnx.rice.edu/cnxml">The angle <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><mi>θ</mi></math> is the angle whose sine is <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><mrow><mfrac><mn>2</mn><mrow><msqrt><mrow><mn>13</mn></mrow></msqrt></mrow></mfrac><mo>.</mo></mrow></math></para>
    <para id="para-00072" xmlns="http://cnx.rice.edu/cnxml"><emphasis effect="bold">Step 3:</emphasis> To find <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><mi>θ</mi></math>, we use the inverse sine function:
    <equation id="eq-00024" xmlns="http://cnx.rice.edu/cnxml"><math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="block"><mtable columnspacing="0.3em"><mtr><mtd columnalign="right"><mi>θ</mi></mtd><mtd columnalign="center"><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd columnalign="left"><msup><mi>sin</mi><mrow><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><mfrac><mn>2</mn><mrow><msqrt><mrow><mn>13</mn></mrow></msqrt></mrow></mfrac></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd columnalign="right"/><mtd columnalign="center"><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd columnalign="left"><msup><mn>33.7</mn><mo>∘</mo></msup></mtd></mtr></mtable></math></equation></para>
    <para id="para-00073" xmlns="http://cnx.rice.edu/cnxml"><emphasis effect="bold">Step 4:</emphasis> To find the last angle, we just subtract: <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" display="inline"><mrow><msup><mrow><mn>180</mn></mrow><mo>∘</mo></msup><mo>−</mo><msup><mrow><mn>90</mn></mrow><mo>∘</mo></msup><mo>−</mo><msup><mrow><mn>33.7</mn></mrow><mo>∘</mo></msup><mo>=</mo><msup><mrow><mn>56.3</mn></mrow><mo>∘</mo></msup></mrow></math>.</para>
    </solution>
    </exercise>
    </example>
